<article class="fyre-comment-article">
  <div class="fyre-comment-wrapper">
  
  
  
  <div class="fyre-comment-user">
    <a class="fyre-comment-author"><img src="http://gravatar.com/avatar/edbb069e18d169338dc830bbc4a9fd97/?s=50&amp;d=http%3A//avatars.fyre.co/a/anon/50.jpg" class=
    "fyre-user-avatar" alt="Heather" /></a>

    <div class="fyre-comment-socialsync fyre-comment-from-livefyre"></div>
  </div>
    
  <header class="fyre-comment-head">
    <a class="fyre-comment-username">Heather</a> 
    
    
    <span class="fyre-comment-user-rating" style="display: none;">5pts</span>
    <span class="fyre-comment-like" style="float: right;">
      
    </span>
    
  </header>
  
  <section class="fyre-comment-body">
    <div class="fyre-comment">
      <p><p>We had large groups of drug addicts around the area where I live in London. When the police eventually had a clamp down the group scattered but soon surfaced a few miles away, just near enough to make scant contact with the previous area, friends, dealers etc. However, successive police clamp downs just scatter and distribute the group further until contacts are lost. With scoring a priority, the lifestyle of the drug addict becomes somewhat chaotic and often beyond the law- all too easy to get lost in the system or elsewhere. Sadly a lot of drug addicts also die and their familiar faces disappear without fanfare.</p></p>
    </div>
    
  </section>

